ce and also to critique it.Chapters devoted to the Western, film noir, superhero movies, and global films that deploy and comment on these genres offer compelling readings of films ranging from the more apparent (The Dark Knight, Sicario, and Logan) to the more unexpected (Sin City, Adieu Gary, The Broken Circle Breakdown, and Tokyo Sonata). Through narratives of states of emergency that include vaguely defined enemies, obscured battlefield boundaries, and blurred lines between victims and perpetrators, a new post-9/11 film canon emerges. No Jurisdiction is a deeply personal work of film scholarship, arguing that we can face our complicity and discover opportunities for resistance through our beloved genre movies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFilm genreszUnited States2DLC. 0aFilm genreszUnited States. 0aMotion pictures and the War on Terrorism, 2001-20092DLC. 0aMotion pictures and the War on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century2DLC. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001, in motion pictures2DLC. 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001, in motion pictures. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848928540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438489285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438489285/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles